1
00:01:32,580 --> 00:01:33,580
Hi.

2
00:01:34,620 --> 00:01:37,620
Okay, here she is, folks. Kitty Dean.

3
00:04:22,460 --> 00:04:23,700
That a girl, Kitty.

4
00:05:27,340 --> 00:05:31,700
It's 38 degrees in New York this morning.
The time is 10:49.

5
00:06:04,540 --> 00:06:07,500
Should I call and get our table for lunch?

6
00:06:10,220 --> 00:06:11,700
Goodie-good.

7
00:06:12,060 --> 00:06:15,420
And Big Mama? Bring lots of gossip.

8
00:06:16,380 --> 00:06:19,140
Everything about him is designed to rivet:

9
00:06:20,660 --> 00:06:24,340
The appearance, the demeanor,
and, of course, the voice.

10
00:06:25,420 --> 00:06:26,580
The voice?

11
00:06:28,100 --> 00:06:31,060
To the lucky person
who has never heard it...

12
00:06:31,580 --> 00:06:37,900
...I can only say imagine what
a Brussels sprout would sound like...

13
00:06:38,100 --> 00:06:41,100
...if a Brussels sprout could talk.

14
00:06:41,300 --> 00:06:42,580
He's so magical...

15
00:06:43,860 --> 00:06:48,020
...you soon forget the most unforgettable
sound in the world.

16
00:06:48,580 --> 00:06:51,820
Here's a word I loathe: eccentric.

17
00:06:51,980 --> 00:06:57,380
Eccentric is a word that boring people use
to describe someone I think of as interesting.

18
00:06:57,580 --> 00:07:00,580
A great many people think of me
as eccentric simply because...

19
00:07:00,780 --> 00:07:04,420
...when I have my shoes polished
I have the entire shoe polished...

20
00:07:04,620 --> 00:07:06,580
...top, sides and soles.

21
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:08,860
Some people think it eccentric...

22
00:07:09,060 --> 00:07:12,260
...that every morning I have my maid
iron my money.

23
00:07:13,220 --> 00:07:16,820
When I told Truman I had my maid iron
my money, do you know what he said?

24
00:07:16,980 --> 00:07:19,700
Here's what he didn't say, "How eccentric."

25
00:07:19,900 --> 00:07:23,460
Here's what he did say, "How wonderful!"

26
00:07:24,980 --> 00:07:28,140
You can forgive a person a lot
who really enjoys you.

27
00:07:28,900 --> 00:07:30,380
He's loads of fun wherever you go.

28
00:07:32,140 --> 00:07:37,100
He's the rarest thing in the world,
a good talker who is also a good listener.

29
00:07:37,380 --> 00:07:40,260
How could Leland
have been bored with you?

30
00:07:40,460 --> 00:07:43,500
Even someone who doesn't speak
English can look at you.

31
00:07:43,700 --> 00:07:47,300
He listened to me the way you'd listen
to announcements in a train station...

32
00:07:47,500 --> 00:07:50,180
...just enough to hear
if there's an emergency.

33
00:07:51,540 --> 00:07:55,820
Oh, well. He's with Pamela,
and I need to move on.

34
00:07:55,980 --> 00:07:57,340
Maybe you can...

35
00:07:57,500 --> 00:08:01,260
...but tout New York is dividing
into the Slim or Pamela camps.

36
00:08:01,420 --> 00:08:03,420
Babe and I are the head Slimites.

37
00:08:04,140 --> 00:08:05,620
Tru Heart.

38
00:08:07,300 --> 00:08:08,780
Oh, have you heard about Tracy?

39
00:08:08,980 --> 00:08:11,020
Yeah. Having her eyes done, I know.

40
00:08:11,220 --> 00:08:15,700
Well, a little more than that.
She's gone off to have an abortion.

41
00:08:15,940 --> 00:08:18,940
Oh, who's the father?
I presume not Dick.

42
00:08:19,540 --> 00:08:21,860
Chas Fitzgerald.

43
00:08:22,020 --> 00:08:23,940
Oh, perfect. Does Dick know?

44
00:08:24,140 --> 00:08:26,460
I think she should just tell Dick it's his.

45
00:08:26,620 --> 00:08:29,060
- She can't. Dick's infertile.
- What?

46
00:08:29,580 --> 00:08:33,980
- Everybody knows that.
- Well, I'm sure they do now.

47
00:08:34,140 --> 00:08:35,620
Did you see the paper?

48
00:08:35,780 --> 00:08:40,700
Yes. There's a story that's stuck in my teeth
like a little piece of pull candy.

49
00:08:40,860 --> 00:08:42,140
What is it?

50
00:08:43,420 --> 00:08:46,820
Well, these well-to-do farm people
out in Kansas...

51
00:08:46,980 --> 00:08:51,860
...were murdered in the middle of the night
in the most gruesome way imaginable.

52
00:08:52,020 --> 00:08:55,300
- Do they have any idea who did it?
- No idea.

53
00:08:55,500 --> 00:08:58,180
But that won't affect the piece
I want to write for you.

54
00:08:58,340 --> 00:09:01,500
I want to explore how a crime
like this affects a town...

55
00:09:01,660 --> 00:09:04,100
...where everyone trusts each other.

56
00:09:04,260 --> 00:09:07,340
It may be preferable that we don't know
the identity of the killers.

57
00:09:07,500 --> 00:09:12,060
Exactly. Because what I imagine everyone
is now afraid of is:

58
00:09:12,220 --> 00:09:15,220
"Who among us did this horrible thing?"

59
00:09:15,420 --> 00:09:20,340
It used to be you'd look at someone
and think, "There's old Mr. Busybody."

60
00:09:20,580 --> 00:09:22,060
Now you think...

61
00:09:22,260 --> 00:09:23,860
..."Did you do it?"

62
00:09:24,060 --> 00:09:27,060
Oh, I can't bear the thought of you
going to Kansas.

63
00:09:27,260 --> 00:09:29,260
Whom will I talk to?

64
00:09:29,460 --> 00:09:32,580
Oh, that reminds me.
Did you hear about Tracy?

65
00:09:32,740 --> 00:09:35,420
- The eyes?
- More.

66
00:09:35,580 --> 00:09:37,100
Abortion.

67
00:09:37,260 --> 00:09:40,700
Oh, I just saw her at Sotheby's.
She bought an adorable Degas.

68
00:09:40,860 --> 00:09:42,580
I wanted it for the guest bath...

69
00:09:42,740 --> 00:09:46,780
...but Bill wants to put the little
Giacometti man we have in the hall there.

70
00:09:46,940 --> 00:09:50,780
Tell him nobody wants to go to the bathroom
and find a little man in there.

71
00:09:50,940 --> 00:09:55,580
- I know it from bitter personal experience.
- T-Bone.

72
00:09:55,740 --> 00:09:58,260
How did you find out about Tracy?

73
00:09:58,460 --> 00:10:02,300
Slim. But I'm absolutely sworn
to secrecy.

74
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:06,900
I'm only telling you
because you're my dearest friend.

75
00:10:07,380 --> 00:10:12,820
Nelle, as my oldest and dearest friend,
do you think the Kansas thing is good?

76
00:10:12,980 --> 00:10:14,340
Are you joking?

77
00:10:14,500 --> 00:10:18,300
That small town stuff,
that suspicion, that gossip?

78
00:10:18,460 --> 00:10:21,580
That is your world as much as this,
maybe even more.

79
00:10:22,740 --> 00:10:25,660
- How were they killed?
- Shotgun.

80
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:29,460
But there's a caretaker not a hundred yards
from the house.

81
00:10:29,660 --> 00:10:33,100
How could he not hear four gunshots
in the dead of night?

82
00:10:33,260 --> 00:10:36,300
Maybe he did it.
Did you consider that?

83
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:39,300
Maybe. Though the victims
were bound and gagged...

84
00:10:39,500 --> 00:10:42,500
...which suggests at least two
in the killing party...

85
00:10:42,700 --> 00:10:45,300
...one with the gun
to make them cooperate...

86
00:10:45,460 --> 00:10:49,580
...and one to tie them up
and make them sorry they cooperated.

87
00:10:50,340 --> 00:10:52,660
The father and boy were shot
in the basement...

88
00:10:52,820 --> 00:10:55,140
...the mother and girl in their beds.

89
00:10:55,460 --> 00:10:59,180
- How do you know all this?
- I called the D.A.

90
00:10:59,500 --> 00:11:01,380
May I tell him who's calling, please?

91
00:11:01,540 --> 00:11:03,860
Yes, dear. This is Truman Capote.

92
00:11:04,060 --> 00:11:07,380
I'm sorry. The district attorney
doesn't take calls from strange women.

93
00:11:10,180 --> 00:11:11,780
And what did you say?

94
00:11:12,340 --> 00:11:14,660
Who says I'm strange?

95
00:11:16,780 --> 00:11:21,140
They can judge for themselves soon enough.
I'm going down there in a week.

96
00:11:21,780 --> 00:11:24,620
Which of your pillbox hats
do you think they'll like best?

97
00:11:26,740 --> 00:11:31,020
Why didn't Jack come tonight?
If he's your fella, he's always welcome.

98
00:11:31,860 --> 00:11:33,180
Truman and I...

99
00:11:34,660 --> 00:11:37,700
...had a taste for one another's company
above all others...

100
00:11:38,020 --> 00:11:42,380
...but we weren't a together-wherever-we-go
couple. He's very social.

101
00:11:43,140 --> 00:11:44,500
I'm not...

102
00:11:45,740 --> 00:11:49,100
...especially with that crowd.

103
00:11:49,260 --> 00:11:51,100
Jack didn't...

104
00:11:51,820 --> 00:11:53,500
...approve of us.

105
00:11:53,660 --> 00:11:56,980
He has the social graces of a syringe.

106
00:11:57,180 --> 00:12:01,380
Jack is just so iron, you know,
he's so, "That's that."

107
00:12:02,500 --> 00:12:04,100
Before he knew Truman...

108
00:12:04,260 --> 00:12:08,420
...he was married to a darling actress
named Joan McCracken.

109
00:12:08,580 --> 00:12:13,060
They were dancers together in Oklahoma!
and he was mad for her.

110
00:12:14,020 --> 00:12:17,060
And then the war came,
and he went away and he came back.

111
00:12:17,260 --> 00:12:20,260
And she told him that she'd had an affair.

112
00:12:20,420 --> 00:12:23,260
Well, he was so humiliated...

113
00:12:23,420 --> 00:12:26,900
...that not only did he end
their marriage that night...

114
00:12:27,060 --> 00:12:31,380
...but he stopped sleeping with women
altogether and he switched to men.

115
00:12:31,620 --> 00:12:32,940
Can you imagine?

116
00:12:33,100 --> 00:12:37,620
Curing your distaste for infidelity
by turning to men?

117
00:12:40,260 --> 00:12:43,220
What if one of the people
you interview is the killer?

118
00:12:43,380 --> 00:12:45,140
And what if he thinks you know?

119
00:12:45,300 --> 00:12:48,100
He's already committed four murders,
you think he'll spare you?

120
00:12:48,300 --> 00:12:51,940
Honey, is this your funny way of saying
you're worried about me?

121
00:12:52,140 --> 00:12:54,700
- Doesn't it seem dangerous?
- Come with me, then.

122
00:12:54,900 --> 00:12:57,500
I can't. I'm trying to write my book.

123
00:12:57,660 --> 00:13:00,140
Well, then it's O sole mio, off I go!

124
00:13:01,340 --> 00:13:05,500
- I don't want anything to happen to you.
- Honey, I'm indestructible.

125
00:13:06,260 --> 00:13:10,300
- Much to everyone's regret.
- Not mine.

126
00:13:11,980 --> 00:13:14,340
Come with me. Your book's all done.

127
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:15,860
Well, I am intrigued...

128
00:13:16,020 --> 00:13:19,740
...but I want to get started on my new book
before Mockingbird comes out.

129
00:13:21,860 --> 00:13:24,980
How near did you say the caretaker lived
to the main house?

130
00:13:26,580 --> 00:13:27,940
Nelle grew up with him in Alabama.

131
00:13:29,020 --> 00:13:32,820
She based the other little boy in
To Kill Mockingbird on Truman.

132
00:13:32,980 --> 00:13:36,020
Aptly enough, she named the child Dill.

133
00:13:36,180 --> 00:13:38,500
People always mention his effervescence...

134
00:13:40,540 --> 00:13:44,580
...but one must remember that at the center
of any bright flame...

135
00:13:44,780 --> 00:13:48,460
...there's always that little touch of blue.

136
00:13:50,860 --> 00:13:53,620
Truman's parents deserted him
at an early age...

137
00:13:53,780 --> 00:13:57,340
...leaving him with elderly relations
in my town.

138
00:13:57,740 --> 00:14:01,820
And Truman always disguised his shame
over the absence of his parents...

139
00:14:01,980 --> 00:14:06,180
...with grand tales
of adventure and glory.

140
00:14:07,780 --> 00:14:10,780
"My daddy can't be here,
he's an aviator."

141
00:14:11,420 --> 00:14:15,140
"My mother's a photographic subject,
but they're coming for me"...

142
00:14:15,300 --> 00:14:18,060
...he would always say.
"They're coming for me."

143
00:14:19,180 --> 00:14:21,700
Every year at Christmas...

144
00:14:21,860 --> 00:14:25,700
...our elementary school did a pageant
through the center of town.

145
00:14:25,900 --> 00:14:30,820
And one year, Truman wrote his parents
that he was the star of the pageant...

146
00:14:31,340 --> 00:14:34,380
...though he was only
a snowflake like me.

147
00:14:35,100 --> 00:14:37,540
But, no matter, it worked.

148
00:14:38,700 --> 00:14:42,220
They wired him to say they'd take
the train from New Orleans...

149
00:14:42,420 --> 00:14:46,180
...and get there just in time
for the pageant. They even said...

150
00:14:46,340 --> 00:14:50,020
...they'd stand right by the cannon
in the square so they could cheer him on.

151
00:14:50,580 --> 00:14:56,580
Well, we marched through town
and as we got closer to that cannon...

152
00:14:56,740 --> 00:15:00,700
...I could see him straining
to see his parents.

153
00:15:01,460 --> 00:15:05,500
When we got to that cannon,
he stopped...

154
00:15:06,180 --> 00:15:10,340
...forgetting we were supposed
to be marching in time to the music.

155
00:15:10,540 --> 00:15:13,100
He stopped and he stared.

156
00:15:17,780 --> 00:15:19,540
They had not come.

157
00:15:24,460 --> 00:15:27,220
I thought for a minute he might break.

158
00:15:30,140 --> 00:15:34,740
And then he threw his arms up in the air...

159
00:15:34,940 --> 00:15:37,700
...and twirled himself all the way over.

160
00:15:42,500 --> 00:15:44,300
A cartwheel.

161
00:15:46,580 --> 00:15:49,380
And then again. And again...

162
00:15:50,420 --> 00:15:52,620
...all the way down the street...

163
00:15:54,500 --> 00:15:56,620
...till his tears were gone.

164
00:15:57,260 --> 00:15:59,140
Truman adored Nelle.

165
00:15:59,300 --> 00:16:03,460
She and Jack were just about
his only non-society friends.

166
00:16:04,100 --> 00:16:07,300
I will say it stung him
when she won the Pulitzer.

167
00:16:07,580 --> 00:16:12,500
He might not have minded her winning one,
but only if he'd already won two.

168
00:16:12,940 --> 00:16:15,540
I've always been interested in crime.

169
00:16:15,860 --> 00:16:18,860
Daddy was a lawyer, and sister too.

170
00:16:19,020 --> 00:16:21,260
I studied the law as well...

171
00:16:21,620 --> 00:16:26,580
...but I either lost my nerve
or came to my senses before taking the bar.

172
00:16:26,980 --> 00:16:29,980
But when Truman asked me
to go to Kansas...

173
00:16:30,860 --> 00:16:33,380
...it was deep calling to deep.

174
00:17:11,100 --> 00:17:12,940
Detective Dewey!

175
00:17:13,100 --> 00:17:15,780
- Do you have any leads yet?
- Nothing I can discuss.

176
00:17:15,940 --> 00:17:17,660
- Detective Dewey!
- Jimmy.

177
00:17:17,820 --> 00:17:19,900
Yeah. Will you confirm that there is
more than one killer?

178
00:17:20,100 --> 00:17:20,940
I will not.

179
00:17:21,140 --> 00:17:24,580
Well, of course there was more than one,
unless the killer was a hypnotist.

180
00:17:24,780 --> 00:17:26,340
Beg your pardon, ma'am?

181
00:17:26,860 --> 00:17:30,580
It's illogical to suppose
there's only one killer.

182
00:17:30,780 --> 00:17:33,140
The Clutters were tied up.
To tie them up...

183
00:17:33,420 --> 00:17:34,820
...he'd have to put his gun down.

184
00:17:35,020 --> 00:17:38,660
Once he put the gun down,
the Clutters would run for the hills.

185
00:17:38,860 --> 00:17:42,020
- I don't believe I know who you are.
- Or what.

186
00:17:43,780 --> 00:17:45,860
I'm from out of town.

187
00:17:46,020 --> 00:17:49,260
- What's your paper?
- Ladies Home Journal?

188
00:17:49,420 --> 00:17:52,820
Oh, I'm not a reporter. I'm a writer.

189
00:17:54,540 --> 00:17:56,180
May I see your press card?

190
00:17:56,380 --> 00:17:59,380
Good heavens,
I don't carry any such thing.

191
00:17:59,700 --> 00:18:03,180
But I do have a passport
back at my hotel room.

192
00:18:03,460 --> 00:18:06,300
Would you like to come back
and look at my little picture?

193
00:18:08,700 --> 00:18:11,020
I'll need not only the facts of the case...

194
00:18:11,220 --> 00:18:14,980
...but how this terrible crime
has eaten away at the foundation of trust...

195
00:18:15,140 --> 00:18:16,740
...that makes up your community.

196
00:18:16,900 --> 00:18:19,700
- I see. No.
- And I... What?

197
00:18:19,900 --> 00:18:22,460
No reporter has special access.

198
00:18:22,660 --> 00:18:27,140
Sir, I'm not writing a news story.
I'm from The New Yorker magazine.

199
00:18:27,340 --> 00:18:30,420
I'm writing a psychological study
of a village...

200
00:18:30,580 --> 00:18:33,660
...and how that place is affected
by a vicious crime.

201
00:18:33,820 --> 00:18:36,580
I will not be careless in my depiction.

202
00:18:36,740 --> 00:18:39,780
I shall labor over every word, every sound.

203
00:18:39,940 --> 00:18:42,180
The final result must be just so...

204
00:18:42,340 --> 00:18:45,180
...as dazzling and unique
as a Fabergé egg.

205
00:18:45,340 --> 00:18:47,020
Right. And I got a crime to solve.

206
00:18:47,180 --> 00:18:49,900
But I don't care whether the crime
is solved or not.

207
00:18:50,100 --> 00:18:51,660
I sure as hell care.

208
00:18:51,860 --> 00:18:55,620
The Clutters went to our church.
They were friends of my family's.

209
00:18:55,780 --> 00:18:57,380
No access.

210
00:18:58,940 --> 00:19:01,900
Oh, you are very, very foxy.

211
00:19:02,220 --> 00:19:05,020
I can see I'm gonna have
to work extra hard...

212
00:19:05,180 --> 00:19:08,180
...to get around
that foxy manner of yours.

213
00:19:08,380 --> 00:19:12,100
Isn't he foxy?
But don't you worry, I...

214
00:19:15,260 --> 00:19:18,380
It was lovely how you didn't care
whether or not the murder was solved.

215
00:19:18,540 --> 00:19:19,980
- Lovely.
- Quiet.

216
00:19:20,140 --> 00:19:21,940
Would you folks care for a cocktail?

217
00:19:22,100 --> 00:19:23,620
Yes, a gin and tonic, please.

218
00:19:23,780 --> 00:19:25,260
I'll have J/B on the rocks...

219
00:19:25,420 --> 00:19:28,780
...with a tiny curl of lemon
and a splash and a half of water.

220
00:19:29,300 --> 00:19:31,860
A what, on the rocks?

221
00:19:32,060 --> 00:19:33,540
J/B.

222
00:19:33,940 --> 00:19:36,340
It's a type of Scotch, dear.

223
00:19:37,740 --> 00:19:40,060
You want me to see if we've got any?

224
00:19:40,340 --> 00:19:42,460
That would be a wonderful beginning.

225
00:19:42,620 --> 00:19:43,740
Yes, ma'am.

226
00:19:46,580 --> 00:19:50,140
I think we need to come in
a little under the radar here.

227
00:19:50,300 --> 00:19:51,980
I know where you are headed...

228
00:19:52,140 --> 00:19:56,020
...but you of all people know how impossible
it is for me to modify myself.

229
00:19:56,180 --> 00:19:58,740
I'm not saying get married and have kids...

230
00:19:58,900 --> 00:20:01,460
...but maybe come in
on little cat's paws.

231
00:20:01,620 --> 00:20:05,980
It's no use.
This cat has long, noisy nails.

232
00:20:06,140 --> 00:20:07,020
Anyway...

233
00:20:07,180 --> 00:20:10,820
...I'll call Dewey's office in the morning
and request a proper interview.

234
00:20:10,980 --> 00:20:13,140
- It might better suit his vanity.
- Thank you.

235
00:20:13,300 --> 00:20:15,620
- Let's start talking...
- Thank you. Thank you.

236
00:20:15,780 --> 00:20:16,940
Thank you.

237
00:20:17,140 --> 00:20:19,420
In the meantime,
let's start talking to people.

238
00:20:19,620 --> 00:20:21,460
We don't need his blessing for that.

239
00:20:21,620 --> 00:20:24,180
I think we should just speak
to people on the street.

240
00:20:24,340 --> 00:20:28,660
Yes, and in our nicest way, the way
that would most put people at ease, say...

241
00:20:28,820 --> 00:20:30,020
Madam!

242
00:20:30,860 --> 00:20:35,100
May we ask you about the gruesome murders
out at the Clutter home?

243
00:20:42,020 --> 00:20:44,860
Maybe you should drop
the word "gruesome."

244
00:20:48,860 --> 00:20:50,060
Sir!

245
00:20:50,420 --> 00:20:51,660
Sir!

246
00:20:53,860 --> 00:20:55,700
Excuse me, sir.

247
00:20:55,860 --> 00:21:00,820
My friend and I would like to talk to you
about the tragic events of November 15th.

248
00:21:01,180 --> 00:21:02,540
Sorry, ladies.

249
00:21:05,420 --> 00:21:08,500
Do you think everyone keeps calling me
"lady" to be mean...

250
00:21:08,700 --> 00:21:11,060
...or can they honestly not tell?

251
00:21:11,740 --> 00:21:16,300
I know I'm not Charles Atlas,
but even Ethel Merman doesn't have this.

252
00:21:16,500 --> 00:21:18,540
No. Hers is thicker.

253
00:21:26,140 --> 00:21:27,700
Mr. Capote.

254
00:21:30,460 --> 00:21:32,700
Is this all? No messages?

255
00:21:33,540 --> 00:21:34,740
No, sir.

256
00:21:35,740 --> 00:21:40,260
I simply don't understand why
Alvin Dewey won't return my calls.

257
00:21:40,460 --> 00:21:42,940
I've telephoned three times.

258
00:21:52,420 --> 00:21:53,740
Nelle!

259
00:21:53,900 --> 00:21:56,220
Care package from Babe!

260
00:21:56,420 --> 00:21:58,380
It's beluga!

261
00:22:01,620 --> 00:22:04,300
Let's get some Ritz crackers
and eat it right now.

262
00:22:04,460 --> 00:22:07,660
Let's. And you know what I think
you should do tomorrow?

263
00:22:07,860 --> 00:22:09,820
Go see the Clutter place.

264
00:22:09,980 --> 00:22:14,300
Honey, if Alvin Dewey won't return my calls,
I'll never see the house.

265
00:22:14,500 --> 00:22:17,180
You know everybody on the planet.
Call somebody.

266
00:22:18,340 --> 00:22:22,660
And please tell the duke and duchess
I am sick to miss the dance.

267
00:22:23,620 --> 00:22:25,100
I will.

268
00:22:25,380 --> 00:22:29,180
Bennett hears wonderful things
about your book.

269
00:22:29,820 --> 00:22:31,860
I almost don't care what the critics say...

270
00:22:32,020 --> 00:22:34,420
...as long as I can be allowed
to write another.

271
00:22:34,620 --> 00:22:39,340
Your dream of being the
Jane Austen of Alabama will come true.

272
00:22:39,780 --> 00:22:42,780
Anyway, Bennett knows
the head of Kansas University...

273
00:22:42,940 --> 00:22:45,460
...who knows the Clutters' lawyer.

274
00:23:12,820 --> 00:23:14,660
The killers came in this way.

275
00:25:04,420 --> 00:25:05,980
Any messages?

276
00:25:08,420 --> 00:25:10,500
Princess Margaret...

277
00:25:11,100 --> 00:25:13,140
...and Noël Coward.

278
00:25:15,820 --> 00:25:18,180
No Dewey. Again.

279
00:25:19,860 --> 00:25:21,820
They're in both ways over there.

280
00:25:22,020 --> 00:25:25,100
Right, but this particular form
goes under last name.

281
00:25:25,260 --> 00:25:27,820
- That whole stack?
- That's the one, yeah.

282
00:25:35,180 --> 00:25:37,020
Is this a good time?

283
00:25:37,540 --> 00:25:39,780
Yeah. Come on in.

284
00:25:43,740 --> 00:25:44,900
Ma'am.

285
00:25:46,380 --> 00:25:48,380
What can I do for you folks?

286
00:25:48,540 --> 00:25:49,540
Well...

287
00:25:50,580 --> 00:25:54,740
...you can begin by serving me
a large slice of humble pie.

288
00:25:55,180 --> 00:25:58,740
I've come to apologize for acting
too big for my britches.

289
00:25:59,060 --> 00:26:02,020
As you see, I even got new britches.

290
00:26:02,860 --> 00:26:05,380
Yeah, well, no harm done.
Real nice of you.

291
00:26:06,620 --> 00:26:09,100
I wanted to explain myself.

292
00:26:09,260 --> 00:26:12,020
I'm trying to create
a new kind of reportage.

293
00:26:12,180 --> 00:26:14,780
Have you read my book
The Muses Are Heard?

294
00:26:17,300 --> 00:26:19,700
Well, it was very well received.

295
00:26:19,860 --> 00:26:24,780
It's about an American opera company going
to Moscow to perform Porgy and Bess.

296
00:26:24,940 --> 00:26:29,460
Now, if I relied only on what
the press managers told me...

297
00:26:29,620 --> 00:26:33,140
...it would have been no different
than a newspaper article.

298
00:26:33,300 --> 00:26:38,020
But I treated the people with the emotional
and psychological detail of a novel.

299
00:26:38,180 --> 00:26:41,940
I see, so you're doing something different
than a regular reporter.

300
00:26:42,100 --> 00:26:43,260
Yes.

301
00:26:43,420 --> 00:26:46,500
And I can't really know how people feel
without your help.

302
00:26:46,660 --> 00:26:49,300
Oh, well, I can tell you how they feel.
Terrible.

303
00:26:49,460 --> 00:26:51,660
They'll feel better when this is solved.

304
00:26:51,820 --> 00:26:53,300
Yes. I agree. And that's...

305
00:26:53,500 --> 00:26:57,500
Look, I wish you well with your project.
But no access.

306
00:26:59,500 --> 00:27:03,340
I'm sorry, but Nelle
and I will have to stay for Christmas.

307
00:27:04,500 --> 00:27:05,780
Why?

308
00:27:05,940 --> 00:27:08,660
Because no one will talk to me.

309
00:27:08,940 --> 00:27:13,340
I've got to stay until they forget about me
and can open up.

310
00:27:13,500 --> 00:27:15,860
No one forgets about you.

311
00:27:16,300 --> 00:27:18,180
What will you do for Christmas?

312
00:27:18,340 --> 00:27:20,940
Of course, everything will be closed...

313
00:27:21,140 --> 00:27:25,180
...so I thought before I'd go to the market
and get a nice cheese...

314
00:27:25,380 --> 00:27:26,740
...some ham and olives.

315
00:27:26,900 --> 00:27:29,820
Slim sent a wonderful Burgundy.

316
00:27:30,020 --> 00:27:32,860
Nelle and I can make a picnic at the hotel.

317
00:27:33,060 --> 00:27:34,700
VELVEETA

318
00:27:40,060 --> 00:27:41,420
Excuse me?

319
00:27:42,060 --> 00:27:46,380
- Could this be all the cheese?
- Well, how much do you need?

320
00:27:46,540 --> 00:27:50,140
Mine is a matter of quality, dear,
not quantity.

321
00:27:50,340 --> 00:27:54,900
Oh, you mean other types of cheese.
Goodness, no. Not here.

322
00:27:57,700 --> 00:28:01,580
- Are you staying for Christmas?
- Yes, we are.

323
00:28:01,740 --> 00:28:04,660
What will you and Mrs. Capote do
for your Christmas supper?

324
00:28:04,820 --> 00:28:09,740
If this is the only cheese I find,
Mrs. Capote and I might try cyanide.

325
00:28:11,420 --> 00:28:14,060
Would you like to come to our house
for Christmas supper?

326
00:28:14,260 --> 00:28:16,420
Really? Like for a party?

327
00:28:16,620 --> 00:28:19,620
It's just not right you don't have
Christmas supper in a home.

328
00:28:19,780 --> 00:28:21,900
That is so kind of you.

329
00:28:22,100 --> 00:28:25,060
Nelle will be thrilled.
May I ask your name?

330
00:28:35,780 --> 00:28:36,860
Hi.

331
00:28:38,060 --> 00:28:39,180
Hi.

332
00:28:41,620 --> 00:28:42,700
What?

333
00:28:43,100 --> 00:28:46,780
We are spending Christmas
with the Deweys.

334
00:28:52,780 --> 00:28:54,220
This just isn't right.

335
00:28:54,380 --> 00:28:58,140
What isn't right is for two people
to spend Christmas alone.

336
00:28:58,340 --> 00:29:00,540
If there's two of them, they won't be alone.

337
00:29:01,340 --> 00:29:02,820
Hi. We're here.

338
00:29:02,980 --> 00:29:05,620
- Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

339
00:29:06,620 --> 00:29:08,620
I know you said not to bring anything...

340
00:29:08,780 --> 00:29:12,620
...but my daddy would kill me if I showed up
for company empty-handed.

341
00:29:12,820 --> 00:29:14,260
We brought you fruitcake.

342
00:29:14,420 --> 00:29:16,580
And she doesn't mean me.

343
00:29:18,660 --> 00:29:20,420
My wife, Delores.

344
00:29:20,580 --> 00:29:22,460
- Truman.
- Foxy.

345
00:29:22,660 --> 00:29:24,380
- Thank you.
- My wife, Delores.

346
00:29:24,540 --> 00:29:25,900
And here is our son, Paul.

347
00:29:26,100 --> 00:29:28,300
Hello, Paul. Merry Christmas.

348
00:29:39,460 --> 00:29:40,940
You gonna watch the game?

349
00:29:41,460 --> 00:29:43,540
I got $25 on it.

350
00:29:48,620 --> 00:29:50,220
Truman, you like football?

351
00:29:51,420 --> 00:29:52,980
Not much.

352
00:29:53,500 --> 00:29:56,820
Though I must admit it always sends shivers
up my spine...

353
00:29:56,980 --> 00:30:00,420
...when the men get inside
that little huddle and whisper.

354
00:30:12,020 --> 00:30:13,140
We have treats.

355
00:30:14,020 --> 00:30:16,580
I have kind of a party question.

356
00:30:17,020 --> 00:30:19,580
I hope it's not too awful or mean.

357
00:30:19,780 --> 00:30:21,660
That sounds fun. Let's play.

358
00:30:21,820 --> 00:30:24,780
Paul Dewey. Don't you wanna come in here
and sit with the grownups?

359
00:30:24,940 --> 00:30:25,940
Since it's Christmas...

360
00:30:26,100 --> 00:30:32,660
...I thought we could all take turns telling
what is the worst present you ever got.

361
00:30:34,020 --> 00:30:38,860
Mine was a shawl from an elderly
neighbor lady. I'm not a shawl lover.

362
00:30:39,020 --> 00:30:41,060
- Me neither.
- They're never warm enough.

363
00:30:41,220 --> 00:30:43,660
Are my ears working properly?

364
00:30:43,820 --> 00:30:47,260
Am I the only one here who loves shawls?

365
00:30:49,900 --> 00:30:51,500
Don't look at me.

366
00:30:51,660 --> 00:30:54,180
My goodness, I love shawls.

367
00:30:54,380 --> 00:30:56,140
I have several.

368
00:30:56,340 --> 00:30:59,340
I think the prettiest one is the one
Jennifer Jones gave me.

369
00:31:00,140 --> 00:31:02,980
Jennifer Jones? The movie star?

370
00:31:03,140 --> 00:31:07,300
Yes. We were in Rome making
a picture called Beat the Devil...

371
00:31:07,500 --> 00:31:10,260
...and I was struggling
to write a scene for Bogie...

372
00:31:10,420 --> 00:31:13,660
...when I began to feel
the most inhuman pain.

373
00:31:13,820 --> 00:31:15,740
Bogie? You mean Humphrey Bogart?

374
00:31:16,420 --> 00:31:19,980
I mean Mr. Lauren Bacall, yes.

375
00:31:20,180 --> 00:31:22,940
I was trying to write a scene for him
and Peter in which they both...

376
00:31:23,100 --> 00:31:24,980
Wait a minute. Who's Peter?

377
00:31:25,180 --> 00:31:26,620
Peter Lorre.

378
00:31:28,140 --> 00:31:31,820
But I had a terrible impacted tooth,
and so John...

379
00:31:32,020 --> 00:31:33,300
- Wayne?
- Garfield?

380
00:31:33,460 --> 00:31:34,540
Kennedy?

381
00:31:34,700 --> 00:31:36,180
Huston?

382
00:31:36,340 --> 00:31:38,660
John Huston, the director?

383
00:31:42,700 --> 00:31:46,860
John told me he didn't care if we had
to shut the movie down...

384
00:31:47,020 --> 00:31:49,340
...I was going to the hospital.

385
00:31:50,180 --> 00:31:51,540
So I thought:

386
00:31:51,700 --> 00:31:56,540
"Well, if I have to be in a Roman hospital
for God knows what length of time...

387
00:31:56,700 --> 00:32:00,700
...I may as well have something with me
to make me feel good."

388
00:32:00,860 --> 00:32:05,340
So I wore the beautiful Balmain shawl
that Jennifer gave me...

389
00:32:05,500 --> 00:32:07,620
...and, if I do say so myself...

390
00:32:07,820 --> 00:32:11,420
...I felt and looked dreamy.

391
00:32:18,220 --> 00:32:21,300
- Did you meet Humphrey Bogart?
- Meet?

392
00:32:21,500 --> 00:32:24,660
My dear, every night
we had drinks and dinner...

393
00:32:24,820 --> 00:32:26,340
...and, once, poker!

394
00:32:27,580 --> 00:32:30,980
You played poker with Humphrey Bogart?

395
00:32:31,140 --> 00:32:32,740
I had a disadvantage in that...

396
00:32:32,900 --> 00:32:35,820
...I didn't know the game
in the way that Bogie or Frank did.

397
00:32:36,020 --> 00:32:36,820
Frank?!

398
00:32:37,180 --> 00:32:38,460
Sinatra.

399
00:32:39,860 --> 00:32:41,420
Experience had taught them things...

400
00:32:41,580 --> 00:32:44,900
...a relative novice such as myself
may not know, like, well...

401
00:32:45,100 --> 00:32:48,060
...did you know that three of a kind
beats a pair?

402
00:32:50,340 --> 00:32:55,220
So, I did not defeat Mr. Humphrey Bogart
at cards...

403
00:32:55,380 --> 00:33:00,340
...but you may be interested to know
I soundly beat him at something else.

404
00:33:08,420 --> 00:33:10,380
Arm wrestling.

405
00:33:11,420 --> 00:33:12,900
Hold on now.

406
00:33:13,660 --> 00:33:16,340
You expect us to believe...

407
00:33:16,500 --> 00:33:19,500
...that you beat Humphrey Bogart
at arm wrestling?

408
00:33:24,420 --> 00:33:26,100
Twice.

409
00:33:33,940 --> 00:33:35,100
You're good.

410
00:33:35,260 --> 00:33:37,580
Good match, sir. Thank you.

411
00:33:38,740 --> 00:33:41,380
Hey. I just beat the guy who could beat
Humphrey Bogart.

412
00:33:41,580 --> 00:33:43,820
Cool. You wanna come over
and see what I got?

413
00:33:43,980 --> 00:33:46,420
You didn't beat Humphrey Bogart,
did you?

414
00:33:48,780 --> 00:33:53,100
You don't think I'd defeat your child
on a Christmas afternoon...

415
00:33:53,300 --> 00:33:55,940
...with everyone here thinking
what they do about me?

416
00:33:56,820 --> 00:33:59,820
That would be a gift of switches
and ash.

417
00:34:02,540 --> 00:34:05,580
But you didn't beat Humphrey Bogart,
did you?

418
00:34:06,420 --> 00:34:09,260
All right. Roll up your sleeve.

419
00:34:09,420 --> 00:34:10,980
No, no, no.

420
00:34:11,660 --> 00:34:13,140
Scared?

421
00:34:28,340 --> 00:34:30,140
Well, I'll be.

422
00:34:30,420 --> 00:34:34,500
Listen, Foxy.
When you're tiny you have to be tough.

423
00:34:35,020 --> 00:34:38,140
This world isn't kind to little things.

424
00:35:11,500 --> 00:35:13,180
So glad you could make it.

425
00:35:13,380 --> 00:35:16,180
- Hope you'll come back. Thank you.
- Thank you. Merry Christmas.

426
00:35:16,380 --> 00:35:18,820
- Merry Christmas. Good night.
- Come on.

427
00:35:18,980 --> 00:35:20,140
Bye-bye.

428
00:35:20,300 --> 00:35:23,020
Foxy, check under the tree.

429
00:35:23,460 --> 00:35:24,140
Hello?

430
00:35:26,180 --> 00:35:28,660
No, they just left.

431
00:35:28,860 --> 00:35:32,700
Well, I know it, but the time flew.
Guess what?

432
00:35:32,900 --> 00:35:35,060
He knows Ava Gardner.

433
00:35:35,700 --> 00:35:37,860
And Humphrey Bogart.

434
00:35:38,100 --> 00:35:41,540
And Betty Bacall. That's Lauren Bacall.

435
00:35:43,660 --> 00:35:47,900
And she got right into the kitchen
and helped. They are so sweet.

436
00:35:55,340 --> 00:35:56,900
Anything good?

437
00:35:57,060 --> 00:35:59,580
Merry Christmas from the queen mother.

438
00:35:59,740 --> 00:36:01,500
She loves me.

439
00:36:02,860 --> 00:36:04,180
Babe.

440
00:36:04,700 --> 00:36:05,940
Slim.

441
00:36:09,020 --> 00:36:10,340
Who's this?

442
00:36:10,500 --> 00:36:13,740
"Mrs. John Stimmell called to invite you
and your friend to dinner."

443
00:36:13,940 --> 00:36:15,260
Who's that?

444
00:36:15,420 --> 00:36:17,620
It says she's a friend of the Deweys.

445
00:36:18,100 --> 00:36:19,300
How nice.

446
00:36:19,460 --> 00:36:23,020
Look, here's another.
"Please call Mrs. Dorn about dinner.

447
00:36:23,180 --> 00:36:24,740
Friend of the Deweys."

448
00:36:25,860 --> 00:36:27,740
Well, that sounds lovely.

449
00:36:29,220 --> 00:36:30,540
Nelle.

450
00:36:31,860 --> 00:36:34,420
These are all invitations!

451
00:36:39,140 --> 00:36:40,460
Then Ava said:

452
00:36:40,620 --> 00:36:45,100
"I'm not afraid of the police.
It's Frank who scares me!"

453
00:36:46,060 --> 00:36:49,820
And Marilyn said,
"Better sorry than safe!"

454
00:36:51,780 --> 00:36:53,460
Marilyn Monroe.

455
00:36:53,940 --> 00:36:56,940
Bonnie Clutter is such a dear and I...

456
00:36:59,620 --> 00:37:01,620
Was such a dear.

457
00:37:01,820 --> 00:37:03,340
Oh, goodness.

458
00:37:03,740 --> 00:37:06,980
It's hard to put a friend in the past tense.

459
00:37:07,780 --> 00:37:12,740
It seems so sad, especially since Bonnie
wasn't well at that time.

460
00:37:13,900 --> 00:37:15,620
What was the matter?

461
00:37:17,260 --> 00:37:19,300
Oh, well, I shouldn't say.

462
00:37:19,540 --> 00:37:23,820
I just don't think she liked
to be with folks so much.

463
00:37:24,500 --> 00:37:28,220
But if you ever did see her,
if you ever did...

464
00:37:28,460 --> 00:37:31,780
...oh, she was always good old Bonnie.

465
00:37:32,180 --> 00:37:34,940
She was going through
the change of life.

466
00:37:35,140 --> 00:37:36,540
That's all?

467
00:37:36,700 --> 00:37:39,300
You try it. It's enough.

468
00:37:42,820 --> 00:37:46,940
Well, there were four of us went
to the house to clean up...

469
00:37:48,460 --> 00:37:49,580
...clean up...

470
00:37:53,260 --> 00:37:55,860
...all the damage and the mess.

471
00:37:57,940 --> 00:38:01,020
We used to go out to Herb's
to hunt pheasant.

472
00:38:02,940 --> 00:38:07,020
It was strange driving out there
knowing what was waiting for us.

473
00:38:08,220 --> 00:38:10,300
The couch where the boy had been.

474
00:38:10,460 --> 00:38:14,980
It was just,
I mean the bodies were gone, but...

475
00:38:16,340 --> 00:38:18,820
...good Lord, just seeing that couch.

476
00:38:19,860 --> 00:38:23,180
Or the mattress box
where Herb had been.

477
00:38:24,700 --> 00:38:26,740
There was so much blood.

478
00:38:28,100 --> 00:38:33,580
There was so much blood.
Sometimes in big, wide pools.

479
00:38:33,740 --> 00:38:37,460
Sometimes in little spatters.
I was going up the stairs...

480
00:38:37,620 --> 00:38:40,500
...and then I saw a big spot
on the banister...

481
00:38:41,820 --> 00:38:43,260
...and I almost...

482
00:38:43,980 --> 00:38:45,420
I swear...

483
00:38:46,660 --> 00:38:50,140
...well, that was worse than the big stuff
on the floor. Because I thought:

484
00:38:50,300 --> 00:38:52,540
"It made it all the way up here?"

485
00:38:55,260 --> 00:38:57,940
I can only say I was a Marine...

486
00:38:58,340 --> 00:39:00,940
...and nothing ever got to me
the way this did.

487
00:39:03,700 --> 00:39:07,220
Herb was one of the most
respected ranchers in this state.

488
00:39:07,380 --> 00:39:10,540
If there was a list that told you how
to succeed with honor...

489
00:39:10,740 --> 00:39:12,980
...well, he just did everything on it.

490
