After the verdicts,
Truman buried himself in the book.

1221
01:35:46,100 --> 01:35:48,740
By mid-'63 it was done.

1222
01:35:48,900 --> 01:35:53,380
Perfect as a diamond,
as tough, as multi-faceted...

1223
01:35:53,820 --> 01:35:55,500
...only this time...

1224
01:35:55,660 --> 01:35:57,620
...it had kindness.

1225
01:35:58,660 --> 01:36:02,340
But we couldn't publish it
until it had an ending...

1226
01:36:02,500 --> 01:36:05,820
...until something had been settled
about the boys.

1227
01:36:06,020 --> 01:36:08,940
There were four appeals,
all the way to the Supreme Court.

1228
01:36:09,100 --> 01:36:11,620
It took five full years
for a final judgment.

1229
01:36:11,820 --> 01:36:17,100
That was hard on the killers, which doesn't
make a dime's difference to me. But...

1230
01:36:29,020 --> 01:36:32,460
Do you have any word yet
about when the book is coming out?

1231
01:36:32,620 --> 01:36:33,900
I don't know.

1232
01:36:37,180 --> 01:36:40,700
You simply cannot conceive
of the agony.

1233
01:36:44,060 --> 01:36:48,500
I've worked on this book ceaselessly
for four years...

1234
01:36:49,460 --> 01:36:54,380
...pouring the whole of myself into it,
head and heart.

1235
01:36:54,740 --> 01:36:57,500
And then to be waiting like this...

1236
01:36:57,660 --> 01:37:01,140
...unable to publish what I've done
until they're hanged.

1237
01:37:01,780 --> 01:37:03,500
I can hardly wait.

1238
01:37:04,540 --> 01:37:09,020
Do you feel that your book is worth
a human life?

1239
01:37:09,180 --> 01:37:13,220
- Well, it's certainly worth Dick's.
- What about the other man?

1240
01:37:13,820 --> 01:37:16,900
His name is Perry.

1241
01:37:17,820 --> 01:37:20,780
I mean, it's just an intolerable position.

1242
01:37:22,060 --> 01:37:25,980
Because to get an ending for the book
means an end for...

1243
01:37:35,020 --> 01:37:38,500
On death row,
you may only write two letters a week.

1244
01:37:39,900 --> 01:37:42,900
Every week, for five years...

1245
01:37:45,180 --> 01:37:47,380
...Perry wrote both letters to Truman.

1246
01:37:47,580 --> 01:37:50,860
Friend Truman, cold in Kansas today...

1247
01:37:51,140 --> 01:37:54,740
...though not as frigid as I imagine
it is in Switzerland.

1248
01:37:55,220 --> 01:37:56,820
How big are those Alps?

1249
01:37:57,020 --> 01:38:00,860
Friend Truman, do you know the song
"Gold Mine in the Sky"?

1250
01:38:01,620 --> 01:38:03,260
It was Dad's favorite.

1251
01:38:04,620 --> 01:38:08,020
Maybe you could use your influence
with the authorities in this shithole...

1252
01:38:08,180 --> 01:38:10,780
...and get me a tape recorder
so I could sing it for you.

1253
01:38:10,940 --> 01:38:12,940
Not much to say today.

1254
01:38:13,460 --> 01:38:15,100
Awful blue.

1255
01:38:16,220 --> 01:38:19,460
God, I miss you. Please write soon.

1256
01:38:19,620 --> 01:38:22,780
You can't imagine what it does to me
when they bring the mail...

1257
01:38:22,980 --> 01:38:24,700
...and there's something from you.

1258
01:38:24,860 --> 01:38:26,220
Friend Truman:

1259
01:38:27,260 --> 01:38:28,940
It's all over.

1260
01:38:29,980 --> 01:38:32,380
Our last appeal has been denied.

1261
01:38:32,540 --> 01:38:35,780
Dick and I are allowed
to have a witness at the hanging.

1262
01:38:35,940 --> 01:38:39,060
We both pick you.

1263
01:38:39,260 --> 01:38:42,700
- You have to come with me.
- I can't.

1264
01:38:42,900 --> 01:38:47,860
I'm getting desperate about my new book.
It's not coming together.

1265
01:38:55,940 --> 01:38:58,380
Anyway,
I thought this was what you wanted.

1266
01:38:58,540 --> 01:39:00,620
I know I said that...

1267
01:39:01,180 --> 01:39:03,260
...but to see him killed?

1268
01:39:05,700 --> 01:39:07,660
It's too much.

1269
01:39:08,500 --> 01:39:10,900
- I don't suppose Jack would?
- No.

1270
01:39:12,740 --> 01:39:14,460
He wouldn't anyway, but...

1271
01:39:15,180 --> 01:39:19,180
...for some reason,
he gets funny about Perry.

1272
01:39:20,780 --> 01:39:23,140
It's like he's jealous.

1273
01:39:28,300 --> 01:39:29,500
Truman...

1274
01:39:33,060 --> 01:39:34,580
...are you and Perry?

1275
01:39:34,740 --> 01:39:36,540
Please, Nelle.

1276
01:39:38,540 --> 01:39:40,540
I'm begging you.

1277
01:39:43,380 --> 01:39:44,860
But I couldn't.

1278
01:39:46,060 --> 01:39:47,540
And I wouldn't.

1279
01:39:50,740 --> 01:39:54,100
I'm sorry, he can't take the call.

1280
01:39:57,100 --> 01:39:58,540
It was the boys again.

1281
01:39:58,940 --> 01:40:00,740
They want me to help...

1282
01:40:01,740 --> 01:40:03,220
...but I can't help them.

1283
01:40:04,260 --> 01:40:07,660
Maybe they want you for comfort.

1284
01:40:12,380 --> 01:40:14,020
Rain is good.

1285
01:40:16,260 --> 01:40:18,860
I hope he apologizes.

1286
01:40:21,540 --> 01:40:24,300
That would really make him sympathetic.

1287
01:40:35,100 --> 01:40:38,100
Hey, Truman. Where you been?

1288
01:40:41,100 --> 01:40:43,140
I thought you were gonna spend
the whole day with us.

1289
01:40:43,300 --> 01:40:48,260
I couldn't get here earlier.
I was making calls on your behalf.

1290
01:40:52,660 --> 01:40:54,380
It's just so late now.

1291
01:40:54,540 --> 01:40:57,940
- Hickock, let's get ready.
- We have some time.

1292
01:40:59,460 --> 01:41:01,660
I have something I want to tell you.

1293
01:41:02,820 --> 01:41:07,780
They're gonna ask if you have anything
to say, and you must apologize.

1294
01:41:09,660 --> 01:41:16,180
- That won't bring them back.
- No. It restores your humanity to you.

1295
01:41:32,740 --> 01:41:34,180
It's time.

1296
01:41:35,820 --> 01:41:39,020
Anyone saying goodbye
needs to say it here.

1297
01:41:46,540 --> 01:41:47,940
Bye, Truman.

1298
01:41:49,060 --> 01:41:50,420
Thanks for it.

1299
01:42:14,060 --> 01:42:15,940
Did he say anything to you?

1300
01:42:18,340 --> 01:42:21,620
He said he loved me...

1301
01:42:22,100 --> 01:42:24,340
...and he always had.

1302
01:43:09,180 --> 01:43:13,700
Richard Eugene Hickock.
Do you have anything to say?

1303
01:43:17,540 --> 01:43:19,980
Just that I hold no hard feelings.

1304
01:43:21,540 --> 01:43:23,140
You people are...

1305
01:43:23,980 --> 01:43:27,620
...sending me to a better world
than this one ever was.

1306
01:43:51,660 --> 01:43:55,660
"The Lord is my shepherd.
I shall not want.

1307
01:43:57,020 --> 01:44:00,340
He maketh me to lie down
in green pastures.

1308
01:44:00,500 --> 01:44:02,660
He restoreth my soul.

1309
01:44:03,260 --> 01:44:07,460
He leadeth me in the paths of righteousness
for His name's sake.

1310
01:44:08,620 --> 01:44:11,380
Yea, though I walk through
the valley of the shadow of death...

1311
01:44:12,940 --> 01:44:16,900
...I will fear no evil,
for Thou art with me."

1312
01:44:43,140 --> 01:44:44,380
Not dead yet.

1313
01:45:12,820 --> 01:45:14,260
I still hear breathing.

1314
01:45:47,100 --> 01:45:48,300
Okay, he's ready.

1315
01:46:36,580 --> 01:46:40,820
Perry Edward Smith.
Do you have anything to say?

1316
01:46:44,020 --> 01:46:45,500
Friend Truman...

1317
01:46:46,860 --> 01:46:50,580
...I don't know what you did,
but the tape recorder arrived.

1318
01:46:53,300 --> 01:46:59,340
There's a gold mine in the sky
Far away

1319
01:47:01,260 --> 01:47:07,620
We will find it
You and I, some sweet day

1320
01:47:09,260 --> 01:47:15,180
There'll be a clover just for you
Down the line

1321
01:47:17,220 --> 01:47:23,460
Where the skies are always blue
Pal of mine

1322
01:47:25,900 --> 01:47:28,500
Far away

1323
01:47:31,060 --> 01:47:33,460
Far away

1324
01:47:35,140 --> 01:47:41,620
We will find that long lost gold mine
Some sweet day

1325
01:47:43,140 --> 01:47:48,860
And we'll say hello to friends
Who said goodbye

1326
01:47:50,860 --> 01:47:55,500
When we find that long lost gold mine

1327
01:47:56,620 --> 01:47:58,380
In the...

1328
01:48:00,220 --> 01:48:01,220
...sky

1329
01:48:01,780 --> 01:48:05,900
"The Lord is my shepherd.
I shall not want.

1330
01:48:06,180 --> 01:48:07,180
He maketh me..."

1331
01:48:18,540 --> 01:48:20,580
Was he able to speak?

1332
01:48:20,780 --> 01:48:22,260
Yes, he spoke.

1333
01:48:23,020 --> 01:48:24,380
What did he say?

1334
01:48:25,460 --> 01:48:27,340
Smith did not speak.

1335
01:48:27,500 --> 01:48:29,860
He apologized.

1336
01:48:30,340 --> 01:48:32,380
Just chewed his gum.

1337
01:48:33,860 --> 01:48:38,100
You saw those two men hanged.
It must be...

1338
01:48:40,740 --> 01:48:42,660
Isn't it painful for you?

1339
01:48:47,660 --> 01:48:51,660
Babaling, life is painful.

1340
01:48:52,100 --> 01:48:56,420
It's the one experience
that unites rich and poor.

1341
01:48:57,420 --> 01:49:01,380
I suppose I'm able to endure it...

1342
01:49:01,540 --> 01:49:05,860
...because I can alchemize
what wounds me into art.

1343
01:49:06,860 --> 01:49:07,900
Yes, but...

1344
01:49:12,180 --> 01:49:14,100
...at what cost?

1345
01:49:16,220 --> 01:49:21,060
It made him the most famous author
in America and very, very rich.

1346
01:49:21,220 --> 01:49:23,980
He moved to Manhattan where, oddly...

1347
01:49:24,140 --> 01:49:28,900
...he had a very good view
of the place he had left.

1348
01:49:39,980 --> 01:49:42,940
Who ever knows
what our hearts will want?

1349
01:49:44,300 --> 01:49:45,540
Who can...

1350
01:49:47,940 --> 01:49:50,220
...defend themselves from it?

1351
01:49:57,220 --> 01:49:59,900
Seeing what's happened to him since...

1352
01:50:00,180 --> 01:50:04,620
...well, despite the bravado
that only appears to be confidence...

1353
01:50:06,140 --> 01:50:11,540
...I have come to feel
with great heart-sickness...

1354
01:50:15,220 --> 01:50:19,140
...that there were three deaths
on the gallows that night.

1355
01:50:19,860 --> 01:50:22,300
He never wrote anything big again.

1356
01:50:22,620 --> 01:50:26,780
Just collections,
fragments pulled together.

1357
01:50:27,980 --> 01:50:33,340
God knows he didn't have to write,
not after all that money on In Cold Blood.

1358
01:50:34,980 --> 01:50:36,580
It's funny.

1359
01:50:36,820 --> 01:50:40,580
It made him, and it ruined him.

1360
01:50:41,020 --> 01:50:42,620
You know, in his will...

1361
01:50:44,740 --> 01:50:47,260
...Perry left everything to Truman.

1362
01:50:55,100 --> 01:50:59,580
America is not a country
where the small gesture goes noticed.

1363
01:51:00,700 --> 01:51:03,620
We're not a country like France...

1364
01:51:04,620 --> 01:51:08,980
...where charm,
something light or effervescent...

1365
01:51:09,140 --> 01:51:10,820
...can survive.

1366
01:51:11,820 --> 01:51:13,940
We want everything you have...

1367
01:51:14,060 --> 01:51:17,620
...and we want it as fast
as you can turn it out.

1368
01:52:00,820 --> 01:52:02,260
friend TRUMAN

1369
01:52:08,380 --> 01:52:11,380
I read an interview with Frank Sinatra...

1370
01:52:11,580 --> 01:52:14,380
...in which he said about Judy Garland:

1371
01:52:14,620 --> 01:52:19,300
"Every time she sings, she dies a little."

1372
01:52:21,260 --> 01:52:23,700
That's how much she gave.

1373
01:52:27,100 --> 01:52:29,420
It's true for writers, too...

1374
01:52:30,660 --> 01:52:33,500
...who hope to create something lasting.

1375
01:52:35,060 --> 01:52:37,740
They die a little getting it right.

1376
01:52:39,540 --> 01:52:42,180
And then the book comes out...

1377
01:52:44,180 --> 01:52:46,100
...and there's a dinner.

1378
01:52:47,300 --> 01:52:49,620
Maybe they give you a prize.

1379
01:52:51,260 --> 01:52:55,380
And then comes the inevitable
and very American question:

1380
01:52:55,580 --> 01:52:57,180
What's next?

1381
01:53:01,460 --> 01:53:03,820
But the next thing can be...

1382
01:53:07,540 --> 01:53:09,380
...so hard...

1383
01:53:12,940 --> 01:53:15,660
...because now you know
what it demands.

1384
01:53:17,980 --> 01:53:19,500
Hi, Nelle.

1385
01:53:19,660 --> 01:53:23,900
I just began my novel
and I had such a good morning writing...

1386
01:53:24,060 --> 01:53:26,140
...that I want to celebrate.

1387
01:53:26,300 --> 01:53:28,220
Want to come to lunch?

1388
01:53:31,300 --> 01:53:34,660
No, honey, I don't care where.

1389
01:53:37,500 --> 01:53:40,820
Just someplace pretty
where we can have fun...

1390
01:53:41,500 --> 01:53:43,460
...and be ourselves.

